SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 1033
By Hensley
A RESOLUTION to honor and congratulate the 2026 Mule Day
Court Fourth Runner-Up, LaiLah Webster.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should salute those
young citizens who, through their extraordinary efforts, have distinguished themselves as
outstanding Tennesseans of whom we can all be proud; and
WHEREAS, one such noteworthy person is LaiLah Webster, who was recently selected
as the 2026 Mule Day Court Fourth Runner-Up; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Webster is currently a sophomore at Columbia Central High School,
where she is a member of the girls' flag football team and manager of the girls' basketball and
boys' football teams; and
WHEREAS, devoted to serving her community, she is a member of the NAACP and
Elevated Young Minds; and
WHEREAS, LaiLah Webster's noteworthy achievement is a tremendous source of pride
for her family, her community, and the citizens of Maury County; and
WHEREAS, the Mule Day Queen and her court play a prominent role in the promotion of
Mule Day, participating in media interviews and serving as hostesses during the festivities; and
WHEREAS, 2026 Mule Day Court Fourth Runner-Up LaiLah Webster epitomizes the
spirit of distinction and the commitment to greatness that are characteristic of true
Tennesseans; her dedication to excellence is clearly deserving of the respect and admiration of
this body; and
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly find it appropriate to pause in their
deliberations to acknowledge and applaud this young woman for her remarkable achievement;
now, therefore,
SJR1033
016789
- 1 -

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor and congratulate LaiLah Webster upon
being selected as the 2026 Mule Day Court Fourth Runner-Up, extending to her our best wishes
for every future success and happiness.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
